<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06032o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06032o">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06032o"> 32(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ you rejoice me</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;Sir Samuel Ferguson&rsquo; Moreover, another Belfast friend and mentor, Dr. Robert Gordon, was keeping him up to his highest poetical self by a series of memorable letters, extracts from which Lady Ferguson gives in her Biography of Sir Samuel, as thus: &ldquo;<mark>You rejoice me</mark>, I speak seriously, by saying you are &lsquo;doing&rsquo;. To be and to do. O Ferguson, these little words contain the sum of all man&apos;s destiny. You are strong, and I would have you strike some stroke that will reverberate down the vista of time. Will you, Ferguson?&rdquo; <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS2"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) 41</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01104i" href="c01all.htm#c01104i">VI.C.01:104(i)</a></mm></dd> </dd></dl>
